The &#x27;cool but funky&#x27; thing is LINQ.  Language Integrated Query.  It can be used to query in-memory lists and arrays as well as build SQL to query a DB, or even query XML files.<p>It is C#&#x27;s support for monads.<p>In terms of var.  It&#x27;s best not to think of it as dynamic like javascript.  You can&#x27;t do this for example:<p><pre><code>    var a = 123;
    a = &quot;Hello&quot;;
</code></pre>
The second line will throw an exception because &#x27;a&#x27; is not a string, it&#x27;s an int.  So it&#x27;s not dynamic like JS.  It simply infers the type when it can so that you don&#x27;t have to type it, otherwise its exactly the same.<p>Interestingly C# does have a dynamic aspect too, and that&#x27;s with the &#x27;dynamic&#x27; keyword.<p><pre><code>    dynamic x = 123;
    x = &quot;Hello&quot;;
</code></pre>
That will work where the var example wouldn&#x27;t.  It&#x27;s a rarely used feature, but comes in useful to avoid boilerplate when dealing with external &#x27;stuff&#x27;, like XML files, JSON, or REST responses.
